  "prompt": "EBITDA cash flow?",
  "response": "EBITDA stands for Earnings Before Interest, Taxes, Depreciation, and Amortization. It is a measure of a company's operating performance and is often used as an indicator of a company's financial health and ability to generate cash flow from its operations.\n\nTo calculate EBITDA, you start with the company's net income and then add back the interest, taxes, depreciation, and amortization expenses. The formula is as follows:\n\n\\[ \\text{EBITDA} = \\text{Net Income} + \\text{Interest} + \\text{Taxes} + \\text{Depreciation} + \\text{Amortization} \\]\n\nEBITDA is useful because it focuses on the profitability of a company's core operations by excluding non-operating expenses such as interest and taxes, as well as non-cash expenses like depreciation and amortization.\n\nHowever, it's important to note that EBITDA is not a measure of actual cash flow. To get a more accurate picture of a company's cash flow, you would need to look at the cash flow statement, which includes changes in working capital and other cash inflows and outflows.\n\nHere\u2019s a brief comparison:\n\n- **EBITDA**: Focuses on operational profitability, excludes interest, taxes, depreciation, and amortization.\n- **Cash Flow**: Actual cash generated and used by the company, includes changes in working capital, capital expenditures, and other cash items.\n\nIf you have specific financial data and want to calculate EBITDA or need further clarification, feel free to provide the details!",
